The upper left 3 × 3 partition of the compliance matrix represents generalized Hooke’s law, eq. (2.4), whereas the lower right 3 × 3 partition represents the shear stress-shear strain relationships, eq. (2.9). The vanishing of the upper right and lower left partitions stems from the absence of coupling between axial stresses and shear strains, and shear stresses and axial strains, respectively. In summary, a homogeneous, linearly elastic, isotropic material is characterized by the constitutive laws given by eqs. (2.4) and (2.9) or combined as eq. (2.10). Only two material parameters are involved in these laws, Young’s modulus, E, and Poisson’s ratio, ν. The shear modulus G can be evaluated from eq. (2.8). The constitutive laws are often presented in the compliance form of eq. (2.10), i.e., strains are expressed as a function of stress. A straightforward algebraic process, however, yields the stiffness form of the same constitutive laws, where stresses are expressed as a function of strains,


